Background

This document is based on “I. Network analysis of liver expression data from female mice: finding modules related to body weight” at the below link.

https://horvath.genetics.ucla.edu/html/CoexpressionNetwork/Rpackages/WGCNA/Tutorials/index.html

It has been adapted to use data generated in this lab for the example as well as other edits where deemed appropriate.

Step-by-step construction of the gene network and identification of modules

#plotNetworkHeatmap(datExpr, plotGenes = colnames(datExpr)[1:20])
plotNetworkHeatmap(datExpr, plotGenes = colnames(datExpr))
## ..connectivity..
## ..matrix multiplication (system BLAS)..
## ..normalization..
## ..done.

# Choose a set of soft-thresholding powers
powers = c(c(1:10), seq(from = 12, to=20, by=2))
# Call the network topology analysis function
enableWGCNAThreads(nThreads = 2)
## Allowing parallel execution with up to 2 working processes.
sft = pickSoftThreshold(datExpr, powerVector = powers, verbose = 5)

datExpr[1:3, 1:6]

# softPower = 6
softPower = 8
#softPower = 80
adjacency = adjacency(datExpr, power = softPower)
# The below plot appears to be nonsense, but I think I got it from the tutorial.
# plot(adjacency)

hist(adjacency[upper.tri(adjacency)])
rug(adjacency[upper.tri(adjacency)])

# hist(adjacency[upper.tri(adjacency, diag = T)])
# Turn adjacency into topological overlap
TOM = TOMsimilarity(adjacency);
## ..connectivity..
## ..matrix multiplication (system BLAS)..
## ..normalization..
## ..done.
dissTOM = 1-TOM

hist(adjacency[upper.tri(dissTOM)])
rug(adjacency[upper.tri(dissTOM)])

The object dissTOM is a gene by gene matrix where the values within the matrix describe a relationship among each pair of genes. This may require a large amount of time so it may be advantageous to save this result so that future sessions may resume at this point.

class(dissTOM)
## [1] "matrix" "array"
# write.table(dissTOM, file = "dissTOM.csv", sep = ",", row.names = FALSE, col.names = FALSE)
# dissTOM <- read.csv( file = "dissTOM.csv", header = FALSE )
dissTOM <- read.csv( file = "dissTOM.csv.gz", header = FALSE )

Use distance matrix for hclust.

# Call the hierarchical clustering function
geneTree = hclust(as.dist(dissTOM), method = "average");
# Plot the resulting clustering tree (dendrogram)
#sizeGrWindow(12,9)
plot(geneTree, xlab="", sub="", main = "Gene clustering on TOM-based dissimilarity",
     labels = FALSE, hang = 0.04, ylim = c(0.7, 0.8))

axis( side = 1 )

# plot(geneTree, xlab="", sub="", main = "Gene clustering on TOM-based dissimilarity",
#      labels = FALSE, hang = 0.04, ylim = c(0.8, 1))

# geneTree2 <- ape::as.phylo(geneTree)
my_dendro <- as.dendrogram(geneTree)
plot(my_dendro, xlim = c(75, 120), xlab = geneTree$labels)

axis( side = 1 )

Use tree to create ‘modules’ (i.e., clusters or groups).

Adjust minModuleSize to get your desired number of modules.

# We like large modules, so we set the minimum module size relatively high:
#minModuleSize = 30
# Or low for small modules.
# Adjust this to get your desired number of modules.
minModuleSize = 3

# Module identification using dynamic tree cut:
dynamicMods = cutreeDynamic(dendro = geneTree, distM = dissTOM,
                            deepSplit = 2, pamRespectsDendro = FALSE,
                            minClusterSize = minModuleSize)
##  ..cutHeight not given, setting it to 0.998  ===>  99% of the (truncated) height range in dendro.
##  ..done.
table(dynamicMods)
## dynamicMods

Methods

In order to group the genes into modules, or clusters, of genes with similar expression patterns we used weighted gene co-expression network analysis (WGCNA; Langfelder and Horvath (2008)) implemented in the R environment (R Core Team 2023). Default WGCNA parameters were used except where specified. Expression data as fragments per kilobase of transcript per million read pairs (FPKM) output by StringTie (Pertea et al. 2016) were used as input. The ratio of CBGA to THCA for each sample was input into R and used as a phenotype. A soft power was selected by plotting scale free topology and mean connectivity as a function of soft power. This soft power was used to calculate an adjacency matrix. The adjacency matrix was used to create a topological overlap matrix (TOM). The TOM was used for hierarchical clustering using UPGMA. The tree resulting from UPGMA and the TOM matrix were used to infer modules (groups of genes) using ‘WGCNA::cutreeDynamic()’ with the default cutHeight setting, the deepSplit parameter set to 2, and the minimum module size set to 20. These modules and the expression data were used to calculate eigengenes, synthetic genes that summarize many genes, using ‘WGCNA::moduleEigengenes()’ and a softPower set to the value determined above. These eigengenes were clustered using UPGMA to determine a threshold for merging modules that may have been similar. This threshold was used to with ‘WGCNA::mergeCloseModules()’, the expression data, and the modules, to update the set of modules so that similar modules were merged together. Associations among the eigengenes and the phenotype, the CBGA:THCA ratio, were calculated with ‘WGCNA::cor()’. The p-values from the correlation test were adjusted for multiple comparisons using the Benjamini & Hochberg method.
